Florida COVID-19 Trajectory

Florida COVID-19 Trajectory

Roy Williams, Gabriel J. Odom, Zoran Bursac, and Mary Jo Trepka

22 November 2020

Introduction

Public understanding of science is critical in times of crisis. The following analysis was conducted to examine the trajectory of COVID-19 in Florida. For phased reopening, the White House has set guidelines for local municipalities in their Opening Up American Again report. In the report, it is highly suggested that:

  1. Local areas show a downward trajectory in the number of positive cases as a percent of total tests over a two-week period, and
  2. Local hospitals have capacity to handle all patients without crisis care.

The analysis begins by looking at the number of new positive cases each day and the number of total tests performed each day. The figures are presented together because as there is more testing, there are likely to be more positive test results. Therefore, the proportion of positive cases is also calculated. Given either a flat or increasing number of tests performed, the proportion of positive cases is the key metric to be used when looking at epidemic trajectory. It is recommended that this proportion not exceed 5%.

Note: 5-day moving averages are used to smooth data.

Note: On 8/31 there was a one-time historical data submission of a large number of cases from a large laboratory. The number of cases for 8/31 in the current report excludes this historical data submission.

Note: a data dump of previously reported results prevented the reporting system from normal processing of lab results on October 9th, causing an inaccurate representation of data for October 9th and October 10th.

The data above show for each day since June 8th: the number of positive COVID-19 tests, the number of negative COVID-19 tests, and the proportion of positive COVID-19 tests to total COVID-19 tests.

Total COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of total tests over the past two months (shown on a log scale):

The average number of COVID-19 tests performed each day increased from under 35,000 in early June until plateauing around 100,000 in July. In August, this number dropped to approximately 50,000 test performed per day, before increasing again in the month of October to over 75,000 tests per day.

Over the past two weeks there was an increase of 2625.3 additional tests performed each day.

Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of positive tests over the past two months:

Over the past two weeks, there has been an average increase of 248 additional cases reported each day.

Positive COVID-19 Tests within the Past Two Weeks

In addition to the overall trend of positive COVID-19 tests shown above, we also show an enhanced view of the last two weeks, depicting a decrease in positive cases during this period of time.

Proportion of Positive Cases within Past Two Weeks

During the 14-day period from 07 November to 21 November, there was a slight increase in the proportion of positive COVID-19 cases reported in Florida. During this time, there was an average decrease of 0.062% per day for new positive cases.

Proportion of Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

These are the proportions of positive COVID-19 tests for the since the second week of June:

Overall, the proportion of positive test results out of all tests increased significantly from approximately 5% in early June to a peak of 18% on July 8th. From July 8th to October, the positivity rate gradually declined. Recently, there has been a slight increase in positivity observed. This number is function of test availability and the population being tested. Given a flat or increasing number of tests performed, an increase in the proportion of positive tests obtained points to evidence of increased COVID-19 community spread in Florida.

COVID-19 Deaths by Day

The reported deaths per day peaked in middle of July for the State of Florida. Subsequently, there has been a decline in the number of deaths reported per day. Currently, there are under 50 newly reported deaths per day.

Note: Due to delays in classifying the cause of death and thus of reporting deaths due to COVID-19, the most recent data will undercount the number of deaths. Specifically, 25% of new deaths added this week were from on or before October 4th. This date indicates a point where 75% of our data is considered complete. For this reason, information following this date were excluded from this analysis of deaths.

Conclusion

During the past two weeks, there has been an increase of 2625.3 additional tests performed each day. There was an increase in the number of positive COVID-19 tests obtained by an average of 248 each day. There was an increase in the proportion of positive COVID-19 tests by 0.062 % each day. Finally, the number of deaths reported per day has declined. There is now approximately a seven week delay in the reporting of deaths. Approximately 25% of new deaths added this week were from on or before October 4th. There is now a seven week delay in reporting of deaths for the State of Florida.

Data Sources

Data sources are as follows:

  • COVID-19 Test Results: The number of positive and negative COVID-19 test results come from the Florida Department of Health: https://floridahealthcovid19.gov.
  • COVID-19 Hospital Census: The hospitalization data is disseminated by Floridas Agency for Health Care Administration: https://ahca.myflorida.com.
  • COVID-19 Death Linelist: This list is created and disseminated by Floridas Department of Health. Deaths are medical examiner confirmed. https://floridahealthcovid19.gov.
